# Stellar Dominion — Prompt Intake Workflow

## Design Partner Integration
This project uses a split workflow:
- **Claude** (claude.ai) handles game design, system architecture, and writes implementation prompts
- **Cursor** (you) handles implementation of those prompts

Claude produces structured prompts with explicit file paths, class definitions, method signatures, scope boundaries, and "what NOT to build" sections.

## When You Receive a Prompt Structured Like This...
Look for these sections and treat them as authoritative:

| Section | How to treat it |
|---|---|
| `### Context` | Background — read but don't re-implement already existing systems |
| `### What To Build` | Implementation spec — follow exactly |
| `### File Summary` | Canonical file paths — use these, don't invent alternatives |
| `### What NOT To Build` | Hard scope boundary — do not add these even if they seem helpful |
| `@export` declarations in code blocks | Must appear exactly as shown — these are the Inspector-tunable values |

## Before Starting Any Implementation Task
1. Read `core.mdc` constraints — especially Inspector-First
2. Check if the relevant system rule (economy, buildings, leaders, galaxy-map) applies
3. Confirm the file paths in the prompt match the architecture in `architecture.mdc`
4. If there's a conflict between the prompt and these rules, flag it — don't silently resolve it

## When Scope Is Ambiguous
- Default to **less** — implement the minimum that satisfies the prompt
- Add `# TODO: [feature] — deliberately out of scope for this task` comments at boundaries
- Never add UI polish, extra signals, or bonus features not in the spec

## Confirming Understanding
Before writing any code on a complex multi-file task, briefly restate:
- What files will be created/modified
- What the entry point is
- Any conflicts or questions you spotted

Then proceed unless the user says to stop.
